  "prompt": "Can the sun melt snow in below freezing temperatures?",
  "response": "Yes, the sun can melt snow even when the air temperature is below freezing. This occurs because the sun's radiation can directly heat the snow's surface, causing it to melt. This process is known as radiative heating. Even if the air temperature is below freezing, the snow can still absorb enough solar energy to cause melting. However, the melting might be slower and less widespread compared to when air temperatures are above freezing.",
